08468nam a22010335i 9780812296563DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20192020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122965637 a10.9783/97808122965632doi  a(DE-B1597)531789  a(OCoLC)1128729473  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR414 7aLIT0240102bisacsh04a820.9/003072200aEarly Modern Histories of Time :bThe Periodizations of Sixteenth- and Seventeenth-Century England /ced. by Owen Williams, Kristen Poole. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPeriodization in Historiography and Literary Studies: An Overview -- tChapter 1. Periodizing the Early Modern: The Historian’s View -- tChapter 2. Time Boundaries and Time Shifts in Early Modern Literary Studies -- tPART I. Religion -- tChapter 3. How Early Modern Church Historians Defined Periods in History -- tChapter 4. Periodization and the Secular -- tChapter 5. Trans-Reformation English Literary History -- tPART II. Materiality -- tChapter 6. Time and Place in Shakespeare’s Stratford-upon- Avon -- tChapter 7. Much Ado About Ruffs: Laundry Time in Feminist Counter-Archives -- tPART III. Poetics -- tChapter 8. The Period Concept and Seventeenth-Century Poetry -- tChapter 9. Love Poetry and Periodization -- tPART IV. Shakespeare -- tChapter 10. Shakespeare, Period -- tChapter 11. Periodic Shakespeare -- tPART V. Self-Emplacement -- tChapter 12. John Dryden and Restoration Time: Writing the Self Within Time, Through Time, Beyond Time -- tChapter 13. Did the English Seventeenth Century Really End at 1660? Subaltern Perspectives on the Continuing Impact of the English Civil Wars -- tPART VI. Beyond Time -- tChapter 14. Space Travel: Spatiality and/or Temporality in the Study of Periodization -- tChapter 15. Always, Already, Again: Toward a New Typological Historiography -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly Modern Histories of Time examines how a range of chronological modes intrinsic to the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries shaped the thought-worlds of those living during this time and explores how these temporally indigenous models can productively influence our own working concepts of historical period. This innovative approach thus moves beyond debates about where we should divide linear time (and what to call the ensuing segments) to reconsider the very concept of "period." Bringing together an eminent cast of literary scholars and historians, the volume develops productive historical models by drawing on the very texts and cultural contexts that are their objects of study. What happens to the idea of "period" when English literature is properly placed within the dynamic currents of pan-European literary phenomena? How might we think of historical period through the palimpsested nature of buildings, through the religious concept of the secular, through the demographic model of the life cycle, even through the repetitive labor of laundering? From theology to material culture to the temporal constructions of Shakespeare, and from the politics of space to the poetics of typology, the essays in this volume take up diverse, complex models of sixteenth- and seventeenth-century temporality and contemplate their current relevance for our own ideas of history. The volume thus embraces the ambiguity inherent in the word "contemporary," moving between our subjects' sense of self-emplacement and the historiographical need to address the questions and concerns that affect us today.Contributors: Douglas Bruster, Euan Cameron, Heather Dubrow, Kate Giles, Tim Harris, Natasha Korda, Julia Reinhard Lupton, Kristen Poole, Ethan H. Shagan, Jam